Problem Specification

  • Cadet Basic Training
    • West Point, NY
    • Over 1000 New Cadets
    • Wide range of fitness backgrounds
    • Pre-evaluated physically
  • High levels of activity
    • 7 weeks of training
    • Rucking, Running, etc
    • Uneven terrain
    • Sleep Disruption
  • Injuries to new trainees are costly to the military
    • Time
    • Money
    • Skill

Problem:

Many cadets often sustain lower body injuries during cadet basic training

Goal:

Identify which new cadets are most likely to suffer a lower body injury during cadet basic training

Definition:

Injury determined as required profile to miss training

What is known about this topic?

  • High BMI and low BMI are indicators
  • Fitness matters


Many false positives if we use a simple heuristic


What does this study add?

Adds provides a more analytical look at risk factors associated with lower body injuries in cadet basic training.

Preprocesses

preprocessing_recipe <-
  recipe(injured ~ ., data = training(initial_split)) %>%
  step_rm(usma_grad_yr) %>%
  step_knnimpute(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_center(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_scale(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_lincomb(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>%
  prep()

Set Up Cross Validation

set.seed(nchar("beat_navy"))
cv_folds =
  training(initial_split) %>%
    bake(preprocessing_recipe, new_data = .) %>%
    vfold_cv(v = 5)

Specify Models

Regularized Logistic Regression

glmnet_model =
  logistic_reg(mode = "classification",
    penalty = tune(),
    mixture = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("glmnet")

Support Vector Machine

svm_model =
  svm_rbf(mode = "classification",
    cost = tune(),
    margin = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("kernlab")

Random Forest

forest_model =
  rand_forest(
    mode = "classification",
    mtry = tune(),
    trees = tune(),
    min_n = tune()
  ) %>%
  set_engine("randomForest", objective = "reg:squarederror")

Execute CV

Regularized Logistic Regression

library(tune)
glmnet_stage_1_cv_results_tbl <- tune_grid(
    formula   = injured ~ .,
    model     = glmnet_model,
    resamples = cv_folds,
    grid      = glmnet_grid,
    metrics   = metric_set(accuracy, kap, roc_auc),
    control   = control_grid(verbose = TRUE)
)

Support Vector Machine

library(tune)
library(doFuture)

all_cores <- parallel::detectCores(logical = FALSE)

registerDoFuture()
cl <- makeCluster(all_cores)
plan(cluster, workers = cl)

svm_stage_1_cv_results_tbl <- tune_grid(
    formula   = injured ~ .,
    model     = svm_model,
    resamples = cv_folds,
    grid      = svm_grid,
    metrics   = metric_set(accuracy, kap, roc_auc),
    control   = control_grid(verbose = TRUE)
)
stopCluster(cl)

Variable Importance

Conclusions

  • While injuries arent knowable, we can identify those at more risk
  • Take special care of those who might need more injury prevention
  • Must be careful about second order impacts of policies
